e reformatted for children, and war-time picture books, Megan Swift elucidates the vital and multifaceted function of illustrated children’s literature in repurposing the past. Picturing the Page demonstrates that while the texts of the past remained fixed, illustrations could slip between the pages to mediate and annotate that past, as well as connect with anti-religious, patriotic, and other campaigns that were central to Soviet children’s culture after the 1917 Revolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChildrenxBooks and readingzSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aChildren's literature, SovietxHistory and criticism. 0aChildren's literature, SovietxIllustrations. 0aIllustrated children's bookszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aIllustration of bookszSoviet UnionxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aPushkin.  aRussia.  aRussian.  aSoviet Union.  aSoviet children’s culture.  aTolstoy.  aWorld War II.  abook history.  abook illustrations.  achildren’s publishing.  afairy tales.  atwentieth century children’s literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266741940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442667419423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442667419.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles